fields.physical_description:
[Leather panel] Gilt leather panel with a pattern of curved and scrolled branches and pomegranates, united by an ornamental ring, and enclosing conventional flowers in gold on a green/blue ground. The gilded parts have been punched with several different stamps. The silverfoil measures 7 x 7 cm (circa). This panel was part of a large hanging, described originally as: Gilt leather hanging consisting of nine panels, together with seven other pieces for the borders on two sides. The repeating pattern consists of curved and scrolled branches and pomegranates, united by ornamental rings, and enclosing conventional flowers in gold on a blue ground. The border at the top is made up of several bands, the broadest of which is decorated with a scrolled floral design. The border on the side is ornamented with arabesques and figures. Both borders are executed in gold on a blue ground. The panel is further decorated with small stamped diapers.

fields.history_note:
Formerly described as 'Florentine, 16th century'. There is, however, no exact information available (not in Italy or elsewhere) to keep this attribution any longer standing. The whole group of  panels and hangings that were acquired from Bardini were, without any exception, being described in this way, although for instance inventory number 732-1890 has proven to be of a Dutch origin. Information supplied by Eloy Koldeweij, October 1996.

Purchase price of £1000 for a group of leather objects (museum numbers: 682-1890 to 732-1890).

[Leather panel] Identical panels are in the collection of Museo Stibbert, Florence, inventory number unknown, mounted on the doors of the storage cupboard for gilt leather.
